title: MLAS: Add MlasComputeSoftmax/MlasComputeExp
body:
**Description**: This adds optimized routines to compute softmax/logsoftmax/exp.

**Motivation and Context**
This change adds:
1. MlasComputeExp function to vectorize exp() over a buffer used for the Exp op. The previous implementation used Eigen but was stuck the instruction set used to build ORT. The new version supports SSE2/AVX2/AVX512F (as well as NEON/VSX).
2. MlasComputeSoftmax function to vectorize softmax()/logsoftmax() for a NxD buffer. This is now used for the Softmax/LogSoftmax/Attention ops. This is optimized for the same platforms as MlasComputeExp.

This also restores threading to MlasComputeSoftmax for 1.3.

For an internal customer model, the changes improved a model from 134ms to 124ms per inference.

title: Update onnxruntime C++ API to enable a workaround for potential crash
body:
**Description**: This PR does not change any behavior or public interface. The only thing it changes is modifying type of `ORT::Global<T>::api_` from a reference to a pointer.

**Why**: the direct purpose of this change is to enable a workaround for a potential crash. The crash is described in the bug [backlog](https://msdata.visualstudio.com/Vienna/_workitems/edit/730320) - the static variable (reference) does not get initialized when use, which is not supposed to happen.

As the root cause is still under investigation, this change enabled a workaround - by changing the static variable from reference to pointer, it's value is allowed to be modified by user.

**Changes**:
 - no public API change, no expected behavior change
 - change `Global<void>::api_` from a reference to a pointer
 - call `GetApi()` instead of using `Global<void>::api_` directly in onnxruntime_cxx_inline.h

title: Add numerical stability to SoftmaxGrad test inputs.
body:
**SoftmaxGrad** tests that verify gradients computed from CPU and GPU kernels match have been observed to fail sporadically on Linux and Windows. The issue seems to arise due to the absence of numerical stability in test input `Y` that PyTorch [softmax_grad test](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/be757957bace28100e571ec7914765020be4a069/caffe2/python/operator_test/softmax_ops_test.py#L69) seems to add. In addition to this we must restrict the domain of input values from **[-10.0, 10.0)** to **[0, 1)** just like PyTorch [softmax_grad test](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/be757957bace28100e571ec7914765020be4a069/caffe2/python/operator_test/softmax_ops_test.py#L69).

**Just by alone adding `1e-2` to input `Y` for numerical stability I was able to resolve below failures.** I have also verified both CPU and GPU implementation are correct. To further verify the correctness of this change I ran both the tests in a loop for 1000 with varying random seed and did not observe any failures on Linux. This change also re-enables SoftmaxGrad_LargeTensor test.

**CudaKernelTest.SoftmaxGrad_SmallTensor**
```
Linux:
2020-05-04T22:35:08.3699287Z 1: expected 2.33688 (40158f69), got 2.2905 (4012979b), diff: 0.0463748, tol=0.0117844. 2939 of 262144 differ
ORT test random seed: 3190010571

Windows:
expected 5.29682 (40a97f97), got 5.42497 (40ad995c), diff: 0.128146, tol=0.0265841. 3518 of 262144 differ

ORT test random seed: 1224836532
```
**CudaKernelTest.SoftmaxGrad_LargeTensor**
```
Linux:
random seed: 552621640
```

title: LSTM performance tweak + cleanup
body:
**Description**: Changes to LSTM operator to improve an internal first party model. Also cleanup the code after other recent changes.

**Motivation and Context**
For larger LSTMs, the zero fills of some intermediate buffers was a noticeable chunk of time. The buffer zeroing is not needed in the cases as the buffer is always overwritten by InitializeBuffers() or the first ComputeGemm in the operator. For an internal first party model, this saved 4ms of single-threaded time (reducing the model from 124ms/inference to 120ms).

Also cleanup the #include files used in this module to simplify the code.

title: [WIP] Separate inference and training frontend APIs in 2 modules
body:
This PR separates all APIs related to training into onnxruntime.capi.training.

**Motivation and Context**
The original code loads in memory all training libraries when `import onnxruntime` is executed, regardless of whether user intends to do inferencing or training. It also imports both APIs in a single namespace, mixing both inference and training APIs.

This PR removes automatic loading of training libraries and also creates a 'onnxruntime.capi.training' module that contains all training related APIs.

This will ease separation of ORT and ORT PyTorch frontend and create a clear separation between inference and training.

It can also ease creation of inference and training packages. Today, an empty __init__.py is created to replace the original training __init__.py during build to remove training API from being loaded on ORT. This PR is a start to replace that mechanism

title: Changes related to the release binaries requiring Visual C++ 2019 runtime
body:
Going forward, the users of OnnxRuntime who consume the release binaries (v1.3.0 onwards) will require Visual C++ 2019 runtime installed on the target machine. With this common theme, this change has several components:

1) Add a user-friendly prompt if unable to import onnxruntime because the target machine is missing any VC Runtime or the 2019 VC runtime. Chances are they are just missing the 2019 runtime because Python (3.6, 3.7, 3.8) itself currently comes with the 2017 VC runtime by default 

2) Remove logic wherein the FH4 feature was turned off for the previous release because we didn't want to take a dependency on the newer runtime dll introduced by the 2019 VC runtime (With this, we use the feature by default, because the compiler has the feature turned ON by default)

3) Doc changes

In future, we need investigate if the C/C# API can do with a similar user-friendly prompt urging users to install the new VC runtime

title: Fix Windows Inbox build failing on 1) building raw api tests and 2) referencing _winml namespace in onnxruntime.dll
body:
Issue:
1) Inbox build fails trying to build raw api tests. These tests reference the raw headers generated for the Microsoft namespace. These headers are not built in the inbox builds.
2) _winml namespace is referenced in the winml adapter causing cppwinrt artifacts to be pulled into the onnxruntime.dll. This breaks the inbox build.

Fix:

1) Only build the raw api tests for redist. Instead of forking the tests to selectively pull in windows or Microsoft versions of the api, I chose to simply turn off the raw api tests for inbox. This is because inbox builds do not produce raw abi headers in the same way (no ABI prefix) and will cause more in depth restructuring of the code.
2) The addition of Unicode support to the winml api was reimplemented to use the onnxruntime::ToWideString helper. This helper was using the CP_ACP flag to convert char* to wchar_t. CP_UTF8 should be used, as CP_ACP refers to the default code page that changes based on system settings.

title: Various changes for automated downlevel test pipeline
body:
**Description**:
1) Add missing test collateral to downlevel test artifact for new tests.
2) Restructure all tests besides imagetests to do test filtering in the getapi() method. This allows for more customizable logic for test filtering without overly verbose code.
3) Add new test filter runtime parameters to ensure that all downlevel jobs can skip all relevant tests and remain green.
4) Rewrite test macro code to work in the getapi() filtering design pattern.
5) Fixes to api tests to get downlevel working again since added tests. This includes delayloading d3d11, and using LoadLibraryExW instead of LoadLibraryW. 
6) Also uses LoadLibraryExW instead of LoadLibraryW to get some scenario custom op tests to run downlevel.

**Motivation and Context**
This PR will allow this Release pipeline(https://aiinfra.visualstudio.com/Lotus/_release?_a=releases&view=mine&definitionId=2) to run with minimal dev overhead. 8.1 Update through RS2 can be queued automatically in response to nightly nuget builds, and other jobs that require access to GPU can be queued quickly by using scripts to natively boot the host to the  RS3-RS5 image. With the test filtering mechanics working we can actually use the success status of the release pipeline as an ongoing quality bar without any dev overhead of parsing through logs.

title: MLAS: tune softmax kernels for partial vectors
body:
**Description**: The code paths to handle partial vectors in the softmax kernels was too slow: speed it up.

**Motivation and Context**
This addresses some of the slowness indicated in #3892. The paths to handle partial 256b vectors used the AVX instructions to load/store data, but these can be slower than handling the data an element at a time instead. In some microbenchmarks of MlasComputeSoftmax with D < 8, the updated sequences can be twice as fast.

There is additional performance to be had from de-virtualizing the softmax kernel, but that will be done in a different PR.

Also, clean up pooling.cpp to use the new helpers to do a vector wide max/sum reduction. The code generated by this is the same.

title: Fix bug in handling of an initializer that provides a graph output.
body:
**Description**: 
A graph output could potentially be provided by an initializer after constant folding. We currently handle that incorrectly by returning the OrtValue for the initializer instead of copying the value into either a provided pre-allocated fetch or a new buffer as we would for any other graph output. So whilst we return the correct value, we return it in the wrong place if a pre-allocated fetch is provided. Additionally we're giving out an OrtValue instance that points to internal data that a user could update causing unexpected side effects to future model execution. 

Update the ExecutionFrame initialization to handle an initializer that is a graph output. Needed some re-factoring as we need to use some of the virtual methods to do this so IExecutionFrame::Init can't be called by the IExecutionFrame ctor as the virtual methods aren't initialized at that point.

Add unit tests to validate.

**Motivation and Context**
Investigating WinML test failure with a model that had a single Shape node constant folded into an initializer.

title: [Node.js binding] add build flag for node.js binding
body:
**Description**: add build flag for node.js binding. Now the main build script can build Node.js binding by specifying flag `--build_nodejs`. 

Building onnxruntime Node.js binding depends on custom steps that utilizes Node and NPM:
```
npm ci --ort-skip
npm run build
npm test
```

`npm ci` is "clean install" that pulls dependencies node modules and run custom installing script. `--ort-skip` is a flag to skip running building in installation stage (which will be run explicitly in the next command). This command will build typescript code (`tsc`).

`npm run build` runs binding's custom building script, which calls **cmake-js** to build binding.

`npm test` will run unittest and some E2E tests to make sure the binding is working.

title: Fix ORT build when onnxruntime_PYBIND_EXPORT_OPSCHEMA is enabled
body: **Description**: ORT doesn't build when onnxruntime_PYBIND_EXPORT_OPSCHEMA  is enabled (when doc generation is enabled). This change fixes it. It also enables doc generation in one of the required CI checks so that any regression in doc generation is caught.

title: [java] Adds a CUDA test
body:
**Description**: Passes through the USE_CUDA flag to the gradle test runner, and adds a simple test to check that the CUDA provider can be enabled and used for inference in the Java API.

Other providers will need similar hooks passed through if they need to be tested by the CI.
